</header>	<section class="entry-content">
		Personal data about customers is increasingly valuable to businesses, and casinos are among the most voracious data gatherers of them all. But unlike others, the gambling industry goes the extra mile to reward patrons for sharing their personal information. That’s <a href="http://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2014/09/01/things-you-didn-know-about-gathering-your-personal-data/Lin0wPeO89OiTdL1Wt51VN/story.html?p1=Article_Related" target="_blank">one surprising lesson</a> from “<span class="s2"><a href="http://www.amazon.com/What-Stays-Vegas-Personal-Lifeblood/dp/1610394186">What Stays in Vegas</a>,</span>” a new book about how businesses everywhere—and the gambling and entertainment industry in particular—collect and use data about their customers.  <a href="http://betaboston.com/news/2014/09/02/when-casinos-gather-data-the-customer-also-wins/#more-16970" class="more-link">Read More</a>
	</section>
